<div id="review_3245738037" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3245738037" />
    <a title="Amanda Hupe" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/11658047-amanda-hupe"><img alt="Amanda Hupe" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1535036536p2/11658047.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3245738037?book_show_action=true">May 20, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Amanda Hupe" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Amanda Hupe" href="/user/show/11658047-amanda-hupe">Amanda Hupe</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/11658047-amanda-hupe?shelf=2021-reads">2021-reads</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/11658047-amanda-hupe?shelf=summer-reading-2020-arthurian">summer-reading-2020-arthurian</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3245738037" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15471404428863414814">“History is not just a tale of men’s making, but is a thing tied to the land. We call a hill by the name of a hero who died there, or name a river after a princess who fled beside its banks, and when the old names vanish, the stories go with them and the new names carry no reminder of the past.”<br/><br/>EXACLIBUR<br/>I have officially completed my Summer 2020 Reading List. It was all things Arthurian Legend and just in time for Summer 2021! Bernard Cornwell’s Warlord Chronicles is definitely one of my favorit</span>
  <span id="freeText15471404428863414814" style="display:none">“History is not just a tale of men’s making, but is a thing tied to the land. We call a hill by the name of a hero who died there, or name a river after a princess who fled beside its banks, and when the old names vanish, the stories go with them and the new names carry no reminder of the past.”<br /><br />EXACLIBUR<br />I have officially completed my Summer 2020 Reading List. It was all things Arthurian Legend and just in time for Summer 2021! Bernard Cornwell’s Warlord Chronicles is definitely one of my favorites when it comes to the Arthurian Legend tales. (Let’s not forget Signe Pike’s series either!) Excalibur is the final book of the trilogy and it ended perfectly. When we started the series, Derfel is a monk, writing the tale of Arthur down (when he should be writing biblical stories) for Queen Igraine. He is old and in the first book, The Winter King, one wonders how Derfel became a Christian Monk when he was a Pagan Saxon fighting for Arthur. In the second book, Enemy of God, Derfel is helping Merlin gather the Thirteen Treasures of Britain in order to bring the Gods back to Britain and rid themselves of Christianity. Now it all comes down to this moment, The Saxons vs. The Britons. The Christian God vs. The Pagan Gods. We follow Arthur, Guinevere, Derfel, Merlin, and Nimue into the final battle that will change history as they know it.<br /><br />“You always were an absurdly emotional fellow, Derfel,’ said Merlin.”<br /><br />EXCALIBUR<br />THE SASS. God, I will miss that Merlin sass like no other. It took a very serious historical epic and gave it moments of pure hilariousness. But overall, this is a very heavy installment to the series. As we know of history, Christianity took the world by storm and crossed countries and oceans. Arthur could be real but nothing has been proven. But we all know the legend and myth of Arthurus, rex quondam rexque futurus–Arthur, The Once and Future King. Just like in all the other legends, Bernard Cornwell paints Arthur as a man of honor, who takes oaths very seriously and also a man of justice. In the last novel, we read about the betrayal of Guinevere. and yeah, Guinevere is the character that you loved to hate. But my god, her development from the first book to the last one is utter perfection. I loved watching her grow and the fierceness that was under the yearning for power.<br /><br />“Do you think I love Lancelot?’<br />‘You wanted him to be king,’ I said.<br />‘What does that have to do with love?’ she asked derisively. ‘I wanted him to be king because he’s a weak man and a woman can only rule in this world through such a feeble man.”<br /><br />EXCALIBUR<br />You tell Derfel, Guinevere! This is one of those series I will reread again and again. As always, Bernard Cornwell immerses his readers in realistic battle sequences. There isn’t a single moment where the battle feels muddled or confusing. It is as if you have gone back in time and watched it for yourself. This series has everything and it gets ALL THE STARS.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15471404428863414814" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


