    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2691285231" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2691285231" />
    <a title="casey" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/68786440-casey"><img alt="casey" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1621653614p2/68786440.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2691285231?book_show_action=true">Feb 03, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="casey" class="user" itemprop="url" name="casey" href="/user/show/68786440-casey">casey</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback " href="/book/show/35850072-excalibur">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2691285231" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6053038161956551585">There are no words that I can conjure into a review that will do this book justice.. but I will try. “Excalibur” is the brilliant and haunting final installment of ‘The Warlord Chronicles’. Captivating and compelling it held my interest to the end. After reading the first two novels in the series, I found ‘Excalibur’ was a fitting conclusion. This trilogy is more realistic and adventurous than any other books on the Arthurian legends, and far more historically accurate on 5th century Britain. Ch</span>
  <span id="freeText6053038161956551585" style="display:none">There are no words that I can conjure into a review that will do this book justice.. but I will try. “Excalibur” is the brilliant and haunting final installment of ‘The Warlord Chronicles’. Captivating and compelling it held my interest to the end. After reading the first two novels in the series, I found ‘Excalibur’ was a fitting conclusion. This trilogy is more realistic and adventurous than any other books on the Arthurian legends, and far more historically accurate on 5th century Britain. Characters and their actions were more realistic compared to the romanticized versions we've seen in movies or read in other books, and I will miss them dearly. Derfel Cadarn is one of the best characters in recent memory. Defer, while he truly grows and becomes a formidable warrior who remains honest and loyal, he never seems perfect and is always a humble knight and a delight to "listen" to. I can't begin to give justice to the characters that Mr. Cornwell has created in Arthur, Guinevere, Ceinwyn, Lancelot, Nimue, Merlin, and many more. Completely unique, but also completely justified in their own way that is still true to the legend and the possible history. Cornwell has a unique gift for writing that is unparalleled in this genre. His battle scenes make you feel as if you need to go take a shower after you read them. They're more realistic with bodies and horses mounting, rusting metal, and the weight of the armor. He doesn't just paint a pretty picture. He makes a realistic yet interesting story that intrigues and entrances you and makes it hard to put the book down. Anyone at all, who is interested in the legends or stories of Arthur, will find these books a wonderful and refreshing read. The only negative I have to share is that Cornwell has left me yearning for more. I think it is time to start the ‘Saxon Stories’. </span>
  <a data-text-id="6053038161956551585" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


